          <h2>Why the Wirral Needs a Dedicated Emergency Plumber</h2>
          <h3 style="font-size:1.1rem;margin:0.75rem 0 0.4rem;text-align:center;">How does the Wirral's housing stock affect plumbing emergencies?</h3>
          <p>The Wirral peninsula has a remarkably varied housing stock. Birkenhead and Tranmere contain some of the oldest working-class terraced housing in the North West, with plumbing systems that have been patched and adapted over a century. Meanwhile Heswall, West Kirby and Neston have substantial detached properties with modern pressurised systems. Our engineers understand both ends of this spectrum and are equipped to handle each. The <a href="https://www.hse.gov.uk/gas/domestic/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">HSE gas safety guidance</a> applies equally to every property type.</p>
          <h3 style="font-size:1.1rem;margin:0.75rem 0 0.4rem;text-align:center;">Does coastal proximity affect plumbing on the Wirral?</h3>
          <p>Yes, meaningfully so. Properties in West Kirby, Hoylake, New Brighton and along the Dee estuary in Neston and Parkgate experience higher rates of corrosion on external pipework, overflow pipes and metalwork than inland properties. Salt-laden air off the Irish Sea and the Dee estuary accelerates the deterioration of external fittings. We carry marine-grade replacement fittings on every Wirral van as a result.</p>
